{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01K2XZzDzeYsE5xeKXoM4Qv1","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→<?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?>\n     2→<project xmlns=\"http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\" xsi:schemaLocation=\"http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0 http://maven.apache.org/xsd/maven-4.0.0.xsd\">\n     3→   <modelVersion>4.0.0</modelVersion>\n     4→   <groupId>io.openliberty.samples</groupId>\n     5→   <artifactId>io.openliberty.sample.daytrader8</artifactId>\n     6→   <version>1.0-SNAPSHOT</version>\n     7→   <packaging>war</packaging>\n     8→   <properties>\n     9→      <project.build.sourceEncoding>UTF-8</project.build.sourceEncoding>\n    10→      <project.reporting.outputEncoding>UTF-8</project.reporting.outputEncoding>\n    11→      <maven.compiler.source>1.8</maven.compiler.source>\n    12→      <maven.compiler.target>1.8</maven.compiler.target>\n    13→      <!-- Liberty configuration -->\n    14→      <testServerHttpPort>9080</testServerHttpPort>\n    15→      <testServerHttpsPort>9443</testServerHttpsPort>\n    16→   </properties>\n    17→   <dependencies>\n    18→      <dependency>\n    19→         <groupId>javax</groupId>\n    20→         <artifactId>javaee-api</artifactId>\n    21→         <version>8.0</version>\n    22→         <scope>provided</scope>\n    23→      </dependency>\n    24→      <!-- <dependency>\n    25→         <groupId>taglibs</groupId>\n    26→         <artifactId>standard</artifactId>\n    27→         <version>1.1.1</version>\n    28→         <scope>compile</scope>\n    29→      </dependency> -->\n    30→      <dependency>\n    31→         <groupId>org.apache.taglibs</groupId>\n    32→         <artifactId>taglibs-standard-spec</artifactId>\n    33→         <version>1.2.5</version>\n    34→      </dependency>\n    35→      <dependency>\n    36→         <groupId>org.apache.taglibs</groupId>\n    37→         <artifactId>taglibs-standard-impl</artifactId>\n    38→         <version>1.2.5</version>\n    39→      </dependency>\n    40→\n    41→\n    42→      <dependency>\n    43→         <groupId>javax.xml.bind</groupId>\n    44→         <artifactId>jaxb-api</artifactId>\n    45→         <version>2.3.0</version>\n    46→         <scope>provided</scope>\n    47→      </dependency>\n    48→      <dependency>\n    49→         <groupId>com.h2database</groupId>\n    50→         <artifactId>h2</artifactId>\n    51→         <version>2.3.232</version>\n    52→         <scope>test</scope>\n    53→      </dependency>\n    54→   </dependencies>\n    55→   <build>\n    56→      <finalName>${project.artifactId}</finalName>\n    57→      <!-- Enable liberty-maven plugin -->\n    58→      <plugins>\n    59→         <plugin>\n    60→            <groupId>io.openliberty.tools</groupId>\n    61→            <artifactId>liberty-maven-plugin</artifactId>\n    62→            <version>3.3-M4</version>\n    63→            <configuration>\n    64→              <bootstrapProperties>\n    65→                <default.http.port>${testServerHttpPort}</default.http.port>\n    66→                <default.https.port>${testServerHttpsPort}</default.https.port>\n    67→              </bootstrapProperties>\n    68→               <copyDependencies>\n    69→                  <dependencyGroup>\n    70→                  <location>${project.build.directory}/liberty/wlp/usr/shared/resources</location>\n    71→                  <dependency>\n    72→                     <groupId>com.h2database</groupId>\n    73→                     <artifactId>h2</artifactId>\n    74→                     <version>2.3.232</version>\n    75→                  </dependency>\n    76→                  </dependencyGroup>\n    77→               </copyDependencies>\n    78→            </configuration>\n    79→         </plugin>\n    80→         <plugin>\n    81→            <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>\n    82→            <artifactId>maven-dependency-plugin</artifactId>\n    83→            <version>3.1.2</version>\n    84→         </plugin>\n    85→         <plugin>\n    86→            <artifactId>maven-resources-plugin</artifactId>\n    87→            <version>2.6</version>\n    88→            <executions>\n    89→               <execution>\n    90→                  <id>copy-resources</id>\n    91→                  <phase>package</phase>\n    92→                  <goals>\n    93→                     <goal>copy-resources</goal>\n    94→                  </goals>\n    95→                  <configuration>\n    96→                     <outputDirectory>${project.build.directory}/liberty/wlp/usr/shared/resources/data</outputDirectory>\n    97→                     <resources>\n    98→                        <resource>\n    99→                           <directory>resources/data</directory>\n   100→                           <filtering>false</filtering>\n   101→                        </resource>\n   102→                     </resources>\n   103→                  </configuration>\n   104→               </execution>\n   105→            </executions>\n   106→         </plugin>\n   107→      </plugins>\n   108→   </build>\n   109→</project>\n   110→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01HnNFa8spKPhpzyRgMeG7nD","session_id":"fc03748e-8f3c-4e9b-a627-5ed371f2cf3e","uuid":"a3de9b3d-39e6-4eb2-8ffe-34efda9d9848"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_017GzeFTXTM2a9aTjad1iMB6","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→FROM maven:3.9.12-ibm-semeru-21-noble\n     2→\n     3→USER root\n     4→# install uv\n     5→RUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y --no-install-recommends curl python3-venv python3-full     && curl -LsSf https://astral.sh/uv/install.sh | sh\n     6→\n     7→ENV PATH=\"/root/.local/bin:$PATH\"\n     8→\n     9→# Shared browsers path so Chromium is cached once\n    10→ENV PLAYWRIGHT_BROWSERS_PATH=/ms-playwright\n    11→RUN mkdir -p /ms-playwright && chmod 755 /ms-playwright\n    12→\n    13→# create venv and install\n    14→RUN uv venv /opt/venv     && uv pip install --python /opt/venv/bin/python playwright==1.47.0 pytest\n    15→\n    16→ENV PATH=\"/opt/venv/bin:$PATH\"\n    17→RUN playwright install --with-deps chromium\n    18→\n    19→# Set working directory\n    20→WORKDIR /app\n    21→\n    22→# Copy all the assets\n    23→COPY . .\n    24→\n    25→RUN if [ -f mvnw ]; then chmod +x mvnw; fi && if [ -f smoke.py ]; then chmod +x smoke.py; fi\n    26→\n    27→CMD [ \"mvn\", \"clean\", \"liberty:run\" ]\n    28→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01HnNFa8spKPhpzyRgMeG7nD","session_id":"fc03748e-8f3c-4e9b-a627-5ed371f2cf3e","uuid":"2aa0035f-f767-4df7-9915-a75296889f8d"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_015H8h2W2jLRk52rtNEMA7p8","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Create folder db2jars/ and copy db2jcc4.jar and db2jcc_license_cu.jar to it.\n     2→# Set Env below\n     3→\n     4→FROM open-liberty:full\n     5→\n     6→COPY --chown=1001:0 src/main/liberty/config/server.xml_db2 /config/server.xml\n     7→COPY --chown=1001:0 src/main/liberty/config/bootstrap.properties /config/bootstrap.properties\n     8→COPY --chown=1001:0 target/io.openliberty.sample.daytrader8.war /config/apps/\n     9→\n    10→# DB2 JARS\n    11→COPY --chown=1001:0 /db2jars /opt/ol/wlp/usr/shared/resources/db2jars\n    12→\n    13→ENV contextRoot=daytrader\n    14→ENV dbUser=\n    15→ENV dbPass=\n    16→ENV tradeDbHost=\n    17→ENV tradeDbPort=\n    18→ENV tradeDbName=\n    19→\n    20→\n    21→#RUN configure.sh\n    22→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01HnNFa8spKPhpzyRgMeG7nD","session_id":"fc03748e-8f3c-4e9b-a627-5ed371f2cf3e","uuid":"84a9d7e2-e069-43cd-853b-7c7390528ebb"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_011UZgMuDTRF5DdywF6QCDme","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# VCS\n     2→.git/\n     3→\n     4→# Maven\n     5→.mvn/\n     6→**/.mvn/\n     7→mvnw\n     8→mvnw.cmd\n     9→**/mvnw\n    10→**/mvnw.cmd\n    11→target/\n    12→**/target/\n    13→pom.xml.tag\n    14→pom.xml.releaseBackup\n    15→pom.xml.versionsBackup\n    16→pom.xml.next\n    17→release.properties\n    18→dependency-reduced-pom.xml\n    19→buildNumber.properties\n    20→\n    21→# IDE / Editor\n    22→.vscode/\n    23→**/.vscode/\n    24→.zed/\n    25→**/.zed/\n    26→.idea/\n    27→**/.idea/\n    28→*.iml\n    29→*.ipr\n    30→*.iws\n    31→\n    32→# OS\n    33→.DS_Store\n    34→**/.DS_Store\n    35→Thumbs.db\n    36→ehthumbs.db\n    37→\n    38→# Logs / temp\n    39→*.log\n    40→*.tmp\n    41→*.temp\n    42→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01HnNFa8spKPhpzyRgMeG7nD","session_id":"fc03748e-8f3c-4e9b-a627-5ed371f2cf3e","uuid":"742233f2-5c16-44ce-b8fc-583f7f4624fc"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_015xep8EHY2vafiN5SogY5Jj","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Java EE8: DayTrader8 Sample\n     2→\n     3→This sample contains the DayTrader 8 benchmark, which is an application built around the paradigm of an online stock trading system. The application allows users to login, view their portfolio, lookup stock quotes, and buy or sell stock shares. With the aid of a Web-based load driver such as Apache JMeter, the real-world workload provided by DayTrader can be used to measure and compare the performance of Java Platform, Enterprise Edition (Java EE) application servers offered by a variety of vendors. In addition to the full workload, the application also contains a set of primitives used for functional and performance testing of various Java EE components and common design patterns.\n     4→\n     5→DayTrader is an end-to-end benchmark and performance sample application. It provides a real world Java EE workload. DayTrader's new design spans Java EE 8.\n     6→\n     7→From inside the this directory, build and start the application in Open Liberty with the following command:\n     8→```\n     9→./mvnw clean package liberty:run\n    10→```\n    11→\n    12→The server will listen on port 9080 by default.  You can change the port (for example, to port 9081) by adding `mvn clean package liberty:run -DtestServerHttpPort=9081` to the end of the Maven command.\n    13→\n    14→Once the server is started, you should be able to access the application at:\n    15→http://localhost:9080/daytrader\n    16→\n    17→## Notice\n    18→\n    19→© Copyright IBM Corporation 2019.\n    20→\n    21→## License\n    22→\n    23→```text\n    24→Licensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0 (the \"License\");\n    25→you may not use this file except in compliance with the License.\n    26→You may obtain a copy of the License at\n    27→\n    28→    http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0\n    29→\n    30→Unless required by applicable law or agreed to in writing, software\n    31→distributed under the License is distributed on an \"AS IS\" BASIS,\n    32→WITHOUT WARRANTIES OR CONDITIONS OF ANY KIND, either express or implied.\n    33→See the License for the specific language governing permissions and\n    34→limitations under the License.\n    35→````\n    36→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01HnNFa8spKPhpzyRgMeG7nD","session_id":"fc03748e-8f3c-4e9b-a627-5ed371f2cf3e","uuid":"ab4981d2-209b-4b98-a40e-d884cd6aef2b"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_018aBkRX1dPQPTk1q5zygEwM","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Daytrader8: Load Testing\n     2→This readme explains how to setup DB2 and load test the Daytrader 8 application with Open Liberty.\n     3→\n     4→## Prerequisites\n     5→\n     6→1. Open Liberty Machine (Server with Open Liberty unzipped at <OPENLIBERTY_HOME>, and a default profile created)\n     7→2. DB2 Machine (Server running DB2)\n     8→3. Driver Machine (Server running JMeter with jmeter files copied to <JMETER_HOME>/bin, and the WebSocket plugin copied to <JMETER_HOME>/lib/ext, see jmeter_files)\n     9→\n    10→## Setup Open Liberty \n    11→\n    12→Build Daytrader8;\n    13→[Download](https://github.com/OpenLiberty/sample.daytrader8/archive/master.zip) or clone this repo - to clone:\n    14→```\n    15→git clone git@github.com:OpenLiberty/sample.daytrader8.git\n    16→```\n    17→\n    18→From inside the sample.daytrader8 directory, build the application:\n    19→```\n    20→mvn clean package\n    21→```\n    22→* Copy target/io.openliberty.sample.daytrader8.war to <OPENLIBERTY_HOME>/usr/servers/defaultServer/apps\n    23→* Copy src/main/liberty/config/server.xml_db2 to <OPENLIBERTY_HOME>/usr/servers/defaultServer/server.xml  (overwrite)\n    24→* Copy db2 jars from the DB2 Machine to <OPENLIBERTY_HOME>/usr/shared/db2jars\n    25→```\n    26→db2jcc4.jar\n    27→db2jcc_license_cu.jar\n    28→```\n    29→\n    30→Create <OPENLIBERTY_HOME>/usr/servers/defaultServer/jvm.options and add any JVM Arguments desired.\n    31→```\n    32→-Xms1024m\n    33→-Xmx1024m\n    34→```\n    35→\n    36→Set these environment variables. matching your environment (or hard code them in the server.xml):\n    37→```\n    38→contextRoot=daytrader\n    39→dbUser\n    40→dbPass\n    41→tradeDbHost\n    42→tradeDbPort\n    43→tradeDbName\n    44→```\n    45→\n    46→## Set up DB2\n    47→Sign in to DB2 machine as db2 user and create tradedb database\n    48→```\n    49→db2 create db tradedb\n    50→```\n    51→\n    52→Note: When creating the database, DB2_APM_PERFORMANCE needs to be off, or you'll get: SQL1803N  The requested operation cannot be executed in \"No Package Lock\"\n    53→```\n    54→db2set DB2_APM_PERFORMANCE=\n    55→db2stop\n    56→db2start\n    57→```\n    58→ \n    59→## Load Database\n    60→\n    61→Start OpenLiberty:\n    62→```\n    63→<OPENLIBERTY_HOME>/bin/server start --clean\n    64→```\n    65→ \n    66→With a web browser go to http://openliberty-hostname:9080/daytrader/configure.html\n    67→```\n    68→Click (Re)-create  DayTrader Database Tables and Indexes\n    69→Click (Re)-populate  DayTrader Database\n    70→```\n    71→ \n    72→Stop Liberty Server\n    73→```\n    74→<OPENLIBERTY_HOME>/bin/server stop\n    75→```\n    76→ \n    77→On the DB2 Server, Put the following into a script (backupTradeDB.sh) and run as the db2 user\n    78→```\n    79→DB=tradedb\n    80→mkdir -p ~/backups/${DB}\n    81→db2 update dbm cfg using notifylevel 0\n    82→db2 update dbm cfg using diaglevel 1\n    83→db2 update dbm cfg using NUM_POOLAGENTS 500 automatic MAX_COORDAGENTS 500 automatic MAX_CONNECTIONS 500 automatic\n    84→\n    85→db2 -v update db cfg for ${DB} using MAXLOCKS 100 LOCKLIST 100000\n    86→\n    87→db2 connect to ${DB}\n    88→db2 update db cfg for ${DB} using maxappls 500 automatic\n    89→db2 update db cfg for ${DB} using logfilsiz 8000\n    90→db2 update db cfg for ${DB} using logprimary 32\n    91→db2 update db cfg for ${DB} using dft_queryopt 0\n    92→\n    93→db2 update db cfg for ${DB} using softmax 3000\n    94→db2 update db cfg for ${DB} using chngpgs_thresh 99\n    95→\n    96→db2 -v alter bufferpool IBMDEFAULTBP size -1\n    97→db2 -v connect reset\n    98→db2 -v update db cfg for ${DB} using BUFFPAGE 262144\n    99→\n   100→db2set DB2_APM_PERFORMANCE=ON\n   101→db2set DB2_KEEPTABLELOCK=CONNECTION\n   102→db2set DB2_USE_ALTERNATE_PAGE_CLEANING=ON\n   103→db2set DB2_MINIMIZE_LISTPREFETCH=YES\n   104→db2set DB2_LOGGER_NON_BUFFERED_IO=OFF\n   105→\n   106→db2 connect reset\n   107→db2 terminate\n   108→\n   109→db2stop force\n   110→db2start\n   111→\n   112→db2 connect to ${DB}\n   113→db2 reorgchk update statistics\n   114→db2 connect reset\n   115→\n   116→db2 terminate\n   117→db2 backup db tradedb to ~/backups/${DB}\n   118→```\n   119→\n   120→Put the following into a script (restoreTradeDB.sh) to run before each server restart. (To make sure the database is in the same state every time)\n   121→```\n   122→db2stop force\n   123→db2start\n   124→db2 restore db tradedb from ~/backups/tradedb replace existing\n   125→``` \n   126→\n   127→Note: If disk writing/reading becomes a bottleneck, you may need to create a ramdisk and restore the database to the ramdisk.\n   128→\n   129→## Apply Load\n   130→On the DB2 Server, restore the database (as db2 user)\n   131→```\n   132→restoreTradeDB.sh\n   133→```\n   134→\n   135→Start Liberty\n   136→```\n   137→<OPENLIBERTY_HOME>/bin/server start\n   138→```\n   139→\n   140→On the JMETER Server, Start JMeter:\n   141→```\n   142→cd <JMETER_HOME>/bin\n   143→./jmeter -n -t daytrader8.jmx -JHOST=openliberty-hostname -JDURATION=180\n   144→```\n   145→\n   146→Preferably, do three 180 second warm up runs and then three 180 second measurement runs with a 30 second break in between each.\n   147→\n   148→Also, a best practice is to reset the database between each run, which can be done on the configuration tab of the application.\n   149→```\n   150→http://openliberty-hostname:9080/daytrader/config?action=resetTrade\n   151→```\n   152→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01HnNFa8spKPhpzyRgMeG7nD","session_id":"fc03748e-8f3c-4e9b-a627-5ed371f2cf3e","uuid":"c35b022c-ddc9-4573-874a-5b86c16498a4"}
